SENATE JOINT RESOLUTION 556
By Walley
A RESOLUTION to honor the memory of Patricia Lee Newton of
Nashville.
WHEREAS, the members of this General Assembly were greatly saddened to learn of
the passing of Patricia Lee Newton of Nashville; and
WHEREAS, Patricia Newton was an exemplary public servant and consummate
professional who worked assiduously to improve the quality of life for her fellow citizens in
numerous capacities; and
WHEREAS, born in Tulsa, Oklahoma, in 1948, Patricia Lee Newton was the daughter
and eldest child of Dr. Kenneth Newton and Mary Rick Newton; she arrived while her father was
attending the University of Tulsa on the GI bill; and
WHEREAS, Patricia Newton's parents met while working on the Manhattan Project in
Oak Ridge, and the family returned to Tennessee and settled in Knoxville after Mr. Newton's
graduation from the University of Tulsa. He earned a Ph.D. from the University of Tennessee,
Knoxville and served as a professor; and
WHEREAS, Ms. Newton graduated from Knoxville Catholic High School in 1966 and
received her Bachelor of Science degree in History from the University of Tennessee, Knoxville
in 1971; and
WHEREAS, Patricia Newton married Steve Rechichar, and they became the devoted
parents of Rachel Rechichar Newton; the couple divorced in 1976, and Rachel lived with her
mother most of the time; while working full time as an attorney, Patricia Newton spared no effort
or expense in making sure her daughter remained her top priority; and
WHEREAS, a trailblazer for women in the legal profession, Patricia Newton graduated
from the University of Tennessee Law School in 1975, alongside very few other women in her
SJR0556
010795
- 1 -

class, and was admitted to the Tennessee Bar that same year, working with the law firm of Sid
Gilreath in Knoxville; and
WHEREAS, in 1978, Patricia Newton and her daughter moved to Nashville, where Ms.
Newton became an Assistant Public Defender for Metro Nashville before launching her
distinguished public service career with the State of Tennessee under the Governor Lamar
Alexander administration in 1981; and
WHEREAS, Patricia Newton began her service with the State of Tennessee as a lawyer
in the Office of the General Counsel at the Tennessee Department of Health, eventually working
her way up to Managing Attorney in that office; and
WHEREAS, during her tenure at the Tennessee Department of Health, she was part of
the legal team involved in the transition to TennCare, Tennessee's Medicaid program, becoming
one of the first attorneys to work on TennCare issues on behalf of families and children,
ensuring their rights to due process; and
WHEREAS, in 1995, Ms. Newton joined the Office of the General Counsel of the
Tennessee Department of Finance and Administration as an attorney, and from 1997 until 1999,
she served as Deputy General Counsel in the Office of the General Counsel of the Tennessee
Department of Children's Services; and
WHEREAS, in 1999, she was appointed by Governor Don Sundquist to be Assistant
Commissioner for the TennCare Oversight Division and was later appointed as Acting Deputy
Commissioner of the Tennessee Department of Commerce and Insurance; and
WHEREAS, from 2003 to 2005, she served as the Deputy to the Assistant
Commissioner in the Bureau of TennCare in the Tennessee Department of Finance and
Administration, and from 2005 to 2007, she served as the Managing Attorney for the Operations
of the Bureau of TennCare; and
- 2 - 010795

WHEREAS, Patricia Newton loved her career in public service and never retired, even in
the face of illness. At the time of her passing, she was serving as Compliance Manager of the
TennCare Oversight Division of the Tennessee Department of Commerce and Insurance, a role
she had held since 2007; and
WHEREAS, Patrica Newton and David H. Lillard, Jr., the Treasurer of the State of
Tennessee, were joined in holy matrimony and enjoyed almost twenty-five years of marriage,
building a wonderful life together; and
WHEREAS, Ms. Newton was deeply devoted to her family, and she always endeavored
to remain true to family values of the highest order; and
WHEREAS, Ms. Newton is survived by her devoted husband, David H. Lillard, Jr., and
her beloved daughter, Rachel Newton; and
WHEREAS, she will be sadly mourned but fondly remembered by her brother, Ross
Newton; her sisters, Michele (Randy) Neal and Maureen Newton; her sister-in-law, Glenda
Newton; her stepchildren and their significant others, Brooke Lillard and her fiancé, Terry
Sween, and Scott Lillard and his wife, Julie Carter; her sister-in-law, Robin Lillard Bates; her
nieces and nephews, Kelly (Chris) Douglass, Jason Newton, Jennifer Newton Greer, Alex
Newton, William Newton, and Julia Newton; and
WHEREAS, in addition to her parents, Ms. Newton was preceded in death by her
brothers, Rick and Kevin; and
WHEREAS, Patricia Newton leaves behind an indelible legacy of integrity and probity in
public life, compassion and loyalty in private life, and diligence and dedication in all her chosen
endeavors; and
WHEREAS, it is fitting that we should remember the bountiful life of this exceptional
public servant and human being; now, therefore,
- 3 - 010795

BE IT RESOLVED BY THE SENATE OF THE ONE HUNDRED FOURTEENTH
GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE HOUSE OF
REPRESENTATIVES CONCURRING, that we honor the memory of Patricia Lee Newton,
reflecting fondly upon her impeccable character and her stalwart commitment to living the
examined life with courage and conviction.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that we express our sympathy and offer our condolences
to the family of Ms. Newton.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy and upon proper request made to
the appropriate clerk, the language appearing immediately following the State seal appear
without House or Senate designation.
- 4 - 010795

